{{Infobox motor race | Race title = Formula Sun Grand Prix | Logo = FSGP Color Logo 250x165.png | Track map = | Series long = Formula Sun Grand Prix | Series short = FSGP | Venue = Racetracks | Location = Varies | Coordinates = | Sponsor = Innovators Educational Foundation | First race = 2000 | First series race = | Last race = 2018 | Distance = | Laps = Most laps wins | Duration = 3 days | Previous names = | Most wins driver = | Most wins rider = | Most wins team = [[University of Minnesota Solar Vehicle Project]] | Most wins manufacturer = | Surface = | Length km = <!-- or |Length mi = --> | Turns = | Record time = | Record driver = | Record car = | Record year = | Record class = }}
{{use American English|date=June 2015}} {{use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}
The '''Formula Sun Grand Prix''' (FSGP) is an annual [[solar car race|solar-car race]] that takes place on closed-loop race tracks. In the race, teams from colleges and universities throughout North America design, build, test, and race [[solar vehicle|solar-powered vehicles]].
Every two years the race serves as a qualifier for the [[American Solar Challenge]] road race.<ref>[http://americansolarchallenge.org/about/formula-sun-grand-prix FSGP Info Page]</ref>
FSGP 2017 took place between July 6 and 8 at [[Circuit of the Americas]] in [[Austin]], [[Texas]].<ref>[http://americansolarchallenge.org/the-competition/ascfsgp-2017/ ASC/FSGP 2017 page]</ref>
== Format and organization ==
===Rules=== * The race consists of three days of freely driving laps around the race track. * The team with the most total laps driven wins. * The total area of all solar cells and related reflectors, etc., must not exceed six-square meters. * The solar array may be reoriented toward the sun for charging batteries for specified time periods before and after race hours. * Strict specifications and engineering scrutiny process is provided for vehicle configuration, safety requirements, and other standards. * Previous races have divided teams into "open" and "stock" classes based on levels of solar cell and battery technologies.
==History== '''Formula Sun Grand Prix''' is governed by the [[Innovators Educational Foundation]],<ref>[http://americansolarchallenge.org/about/innovators-educational-foundation IEF Info Page]</ref> and was started in summer 2000 at [[Heartland Park Topeka|Heartland Park]] race track in [[Topeka, Kansas|Topeka]], [[Kansas]], in conjunction with a [[solar bike|solar-bike]] race.
It has served as a qualifying race for the biennial [[American Solar Challenge]] road race.
The race was held there every year through 2005 until the 2007 American Solar Challenge was canceled due to funding issues. It resumed in 2009 and has been held every year since then at a few different venues.
===2000=== The inaugural race was held at [[Heartland Park Topeka]] race track in [[Topeka]], [[Kansas]]. It was won by [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]]'s ''Solar Phantom V''.<ref>[http://www.rose-hulman.edu/SolarPhantom/fsgp2000.html RHIT history]</ref> The stock class was won by the [[Missouri University of Science and Technology|University of Missouri-Rolla]]'s ''Solar Miner II''.
