The '''London Tornado of 1091''' <!--is it recorded in the [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]? not in excerpt [http://www.timeref.com/asc1091.htm Anglo-Saxon Chronicle: 1091]--> is reckoned by modern assessment of the reports as possibly a [[TORRO Scale|T8 tornado]] (roughly equal to an [[Fujita scale|F4 tornado]]) which occurred in London in the [[Kingdom of England]] and was the earliest reported tornado in that area, occurring on Friday, 17 October 1091.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tornado/country.html|title=Tornado Country — NOVA - PBS|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref> The wooden [[London Bridge]] was demolished, and the church of [[St. Mary-le-Bow]] in the [[city of London]] was badly damaged; four rafters {{convert|26|ft|m}} long were driven into the ground with such force that only {{convert|4|ft|m}} protruded above the surface. Other churches in the area were demolished, as were over 600 (mostly wooden) houses. For all the damage inflicted, the tornado claimed just two known victims from a population of about 18,000.<ref name=london_019>{{Cite book|last=Schofield|first=John|last2=Vince|first2=Alan|author2-link=Alan Vince|title=Medieval Towns: The Archaeology of British Towns in Their European Setting|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|year=2003|isbn=978-0-8264-6002-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Qu7QLC7g7VgC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=london+population+1100+-+1300|page=26|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=TORRO>{{cite web|title=British & European Tornado Extremes|url=http://www.torro.org.uk/site/whirlwind_info.php|publisher=The Tornado & Storm Research Organisation (TORRO)|accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref>
