}} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header = | Header caption = | Ship class = Oil Production Platform | Ship tonnage = {{GT|33,000}} | Ship displacement = | Ship length = | Ship beam = | Ship height = | Ship draught = | Ship depth = | Ship decks = | Ship deck clearance = | Ship sail plan = | Ship power = | Ship propulsion = | Ship speed = | Ship capacity =*Oil: {{convert|180000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} *gas: {{convert|7200000|m3/d|abbr=on}} | Ship crew = | Ship notes = <ref name=conversion>{{Cite conference | last1=Fachetti | first1=Marina B. | last2=Valério | first2=Cid G.P. | last3=Loureiro | first3=José E. | last4=Jorge | first4=Henídio Q. | title=The Conversion of Spirit of Columbus Semi-submersible into Petrobras 36 | conference=Offshore Technology Conference | location=Houston, Texas | url=http://www.onepetro.org/mslib/servlet/onepetropreview?id=OTC-12140-MS&soc=OTC | date=1–4 May 2000 | accessdate=2010-06-16}}</ref> }} |} '''''Petrobras 36''''' ('''''P-36''''') was at the time the largest floating [[semi-submersible]] [[oil platform]] in the world prior to its sinking on 20 March 2001.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Petrobras P-36 | url=http://www.bluestarline.org/farstad/p36.html | work=Bluestarline | date= | accessdate=22 November 2010}}</ref> It was owned by [[Petrobras]], a semi-public [[Brazil]]ian [[Petroleum|oil]] company headquartered in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Investor Relations | title=Shareholders' Information | url=http://www2.petrobras.com.br/ri/ing/InformacoesAcionistas/ComposicaoCapitalSocial.asp | publisher=Petrobras | date= | accessdate=20 May 2010 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530215456/http://www2.petrobras.com.br/ri/ing/InformacoesAcionistas/ComposicaoCapitalSocial.asp | archivedate=30 May 2010 | df= }}</ref> The cost of the platform was US$350 million (currently US${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|350000000|2001|r=-6}}}}).{{Inflation-fn|US}}
The vessel was built at the [[Fincantieri]] shipyard in [[Genoa]], [[Italy]] in 1995 as a [[drilling rig]]. She was owned then by Società Armamento Navi Appoggio S.p.A. The {{convert|33000|t|ST}} rig was converted by Davie Industry, Levis, [[Canada]] to the world's largest oil production platform.
''P-36'' was operating for Petrobras on the [[Roncador Oil Field]], {{convert|130|km|mi|-1}} off the [[Brazil]]ian coast, producing about {{convert|84000|oilbbl|m3}} of crude per day.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Petrobras P-36 | url=http://home.versatel.nl/the_sims/rig/p36.htm | work=Oil Rig Disasters | date=14 April 2008 | accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref>
P-36 was replaced by FPSO-Brasil which is a leased vessel from SBM Offshore. The FPSO-Brasil started its lease contract with Petrobras in December 2002.
==Accident== In the early hours of March 15, 2001 there were two explosions in the aft starboard column at or around the emergency drain tank. The first explosion was caused by an overpressure event, the second by ignition of leaking hydrocarbon vapor.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Petrobras Platform P-36 Explosions, Brazil | url=http://www.mace.manchester.ac.uk/project/research/structures/strucfire/CaseStudy/HistoricFires/Other/petrobras.htm | work=Oil Rig Disasters | date=14 April 2008 | accessdate=19 August 2010}}</ref> At the time there were 175 people on the rig; 11 were killed. Following the explosions, the rig developed a 16° [[List (watercraft)|list]], sufficient to allow down-flooding from the submerged fairlead boxes.
[[Marine salvage]] teams tried over the weekend to save the platform by pumping [[nitrogen]] and [[compressed air]] into the tanks to expel the water, but they abandoned the rig after bad weather.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/1233083.stm| title=Post mortem into rig disaster begins| date=21 March 2001| publisher=BBC| first=Tom| last=Gibb}}</ref>
The platform sank five days after the explosions (March 20), in {{convert|1200|m|ft|-1|abbr=on}} of water with an estimated {{convert|1500|t|short ton}} of [[crude oil]] remaining on board.
